    "summary": "During a journalism career of more than 25 years, I have reported and edited out of more than 20  countries with Reuters, the AP and Dow Jones. My goal is to produce and lead insightful, thought-provoking journalism that goes beyond everyday news. The need for in-depth, balanced coverage of world events is arguably greater than ever. As Amsterdam Bureau Chief for Reuters I lead a small team in the Netherlands covering politics & general news, business & economics and the various courts in The Hague. Most recently, I have been focused on war crimes in Ukraine and chemical weapons use in Syria.\n\nFinancial Times correspondent for Indonesia. Followed the rebound of Indonesia's economy amid an Asian commodities boom and the struggles of the world's largest Muslim-majority nation to find its footing as a budding democracy.\n\nAssociated Press bureau chief, Indonesia. Overseeing editorial output of a team of 15 reporters, photographers and TV journalists. Assisted nuclear crisis coverage in South Korea, Sri Lanka's civil war and the struggles of the emerging nation of East Timor. \n\nWAR CRIMES & INTERNATIONAL LAW (2000-2006): Opened AP bureau in The Hague. Spearheaded AP's war crimes coverage amid an evolving international justice system. Covered the trial of late Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, founding of the International Criminal Court and proceedings of Saddam Hussein and the Abu Ghraib prison scandal in Iraq.\n\nGENERAL: (1999-2004) AP general assignments reporter in Amsterdam, Netherlands. Followed the immigration crisis triggered by the assassination of a Dutch filmmaker by an Islamist hardliner. Covered national politics and health, including legalized euthanasia and marijuana.\n\nFINANCE: (1996-1999) Business reporter at Dow Jones Newswires on technology beat. Covered equities, bonds and marco-economics through the launch of the Euro, Dotcom boom and 1997-1998 Asian financial crisis.\n\nSpecialties: LANGUAGE & ASSOCIATIONS: Bilingual Dutch-English. Conversational French, Spanish and Indonesian. Member of Reuters Peer Support Network, which helps colleagues deal with the mental strain of working in journalism. Founding member of Association of Journalists at the International Criminal Court. Experienced teacher of media skills and volunteer international journalism school guest lecturer.",
